issue.title: find_or_create_by not working?
issue.body:
*Mongoid 2.3.4*
*MongoDB 2.0.1* 

I have a `Counter` document defined as:

```ruby
class Counter
  include Mongoid::Document
  
  field :collection_name, type: String
  field :count,           type: Integer, :default => 1
    
  validates_presence_of  :collection_name
  validates_presence_of  :count

  def self.next(collection_name)
    counter = Counter.find_or_create_by(:collection_name => collection_name)
    counter.update({
      '$inc' => { 'count' => 1}
    })
    counter.count
  end
end
```

In Rails console, when I run `find_or_create_by(:collection_name => 'MyCollection')`, the returned `Counter`'s `:collection_name ` remains `nil`:

```ruby
Counter.find_or_create_by(:collection_name => "MyCollection")
=> #<Counter _id: 4effe6581d9ba710a5000002, _type: nil, collection_name: nil, count: 1> 
```

In the DB, the documented is persisted as:

```json
{ "_id" : ObjectId("4effe84d1d9ba710b4000006"), "count" : 1 }
```

Seems to me that the validation should also have failed.


Is this a bug or am I doing something wrong?

Bug 7073: GetCOinSBiblio should take $record object, not biblionumber

This patch changes the GetCOinsBiblio subroutine to take a MARC record object
(as returned from GetMarcBiblio) instead of a biblionumber.  The first thing the subroutine
did was GetMarcBiblio, and the $biblionumber passed was never used again.

This subroutine was only used 3 places: opac/opac-search.pl, opac/opac-detail.pl,
and C4/VirtualShelves/Page.pm.  In the first and last cases, it was used in a loop.
In the last two cases, a call to GetMarcBiblio had already been done.  This is expensive, and
we were doing it twice per record.

For opac/opac-search.pl, the call to GetMarcBiblio was moved to just outside GetCOinSBiblio;
this will not change the performance at all.  But for opac/opac-detail.pl and C4/VirtualShelves/Page.pm,
a redudant call to GetMarcBiblio is now avoided.

7146 (Update timestamps when deleting a biblio)

Currently, when you delete an item, the timestamp column in deleteditems is
updated with current time. (This comes from an [unintentional] additional
update statement in DelItem.) It makes deletion time visible.
In the past, the marcxml was updated too at that moment, resulting in an
updated timestamp in biblioitems too. The timestamp in biblio was not touched.

If you delete a biblio however, the timestamps in deletedbiblio and
deletedbiblioitems do not reflect time of deletion. They still show the time of
last update before the record was deleted. This last update can be extracted
from MARC field 005 too.

This behavior is not consistent nor logical. I would suggest to add a statement
in DelBiblio to force updating the timestamp in deletedbiblio(items) too. It
makes the time of deletion visible in the record too. The time of deletion of a
biblio can be very useful for e.g. synchronizing purposes.

Bug 7073: GetCOinSBiblio should take $record object, not biblionumber

This patch changes the GetCOinsBiblio subroutine to take a MARC record object
(as returned from GetMarcBiblio) instead of a biblionumber.  The first thing the subroutine

The freeze is not a deadlock issue, but rather a delay waiting for the socket.connect() call to timeout. This is expected to happen if a connection attempt is made to a host+port that will not respond. That some domains failed to connect immediately is a result of not finding any host IP to connect to at all.

commits.message:
Optimize (cached) Tweet Digest response time

For a digest with 5 users, the fully cached case would require 317ms to serve
the request. 67% of that went to simplejson.loads. By adding trim_user=1, the
response JSON is much smaller, and is parsed faster. We still need to fetch the
user separately, but that means that we're only parsing that JSON once instead
of 40 times (once per status). The response time goes to 229ms.

Since we now make two Twitter API requests per user, even in the fully cached
case the caching overhead becomes noticeable. This is because python-twitter
first calls GetCachedTime (to see if the entry is valid) and then Get (if it is).
We would make the same memcache RPC for both requests (we store the cached
timestamp along with the cached value). By adding a "last request" cache, we
can avoid the second RPC for valid cache entries (true most of the time). This
makes the response time go to 190ms.

All response times were measured on the dev server (average of 4 requests)

issue.title: scrollback.js
issue.body:
Fairly obvious: when a petal is opened onto an existing scene, we want to at least fill the terminal (and possibly push backwards into an ncurses pad by another terminal-height or two) with scrollback loaded from the Hub. @eboyjr already discussed a sane discrete, elective scrollback-acquisition protocol for this.

- dynamically load more scrollback as the user tries to scroll upwards

----

There are issues with this worth worrying about; as some plugins might wish to analysis of much more scrollback than we have loaded, or otherwise expect a “stale” petal (with lots of scrollback) when they're loaded into a “fresh” one (which has to load any scrollback it needs, dynamically.) How do we make those use-cases happy, *without* loading a metric fuckton of scrollback the moment the user opens a petal?

- force those plugins to offload some of their code into a serverscript to do the scrollback-requiring portion of their work?
- just allow them to load a fuckton if they need it, thus possibly affecting the user's experience?
